ic and familial violence: “So, like, I’d never let anyone hit me but I’ve hit them, and I shouldn’t have done” -- tThinking about sociological work on personal and family life in the light of research on young people’s experience of parental substance misuse -- tThe trouble with siblings: some psychosocial thoughts about sisters, aggression and femininity -- tChildren and family transitions: contact and togetherness -- tTroubles and Transitions Across Space and Culture -- t‘Troubling’ or ‘ordinary’? Children’s views on migration and intergenerational ethnic identities -- tColombian families dealing with parents’ international migration -- tFamilies left behind: unaccompanied young people seeking asylum in the UK -- tYoung people’s caring relations and transitions within families affected by HIV -- tEstimating the prevalence of forced marriage in England -- tWorking with Families -- tEuropean perspectives on parenting and family support -- tWhat supports resilient coping among family members? A systemic practitioner’s perspective -- tTroubled and troublesome teens: mothers’ and professionals’ understandings of parenting teenagers and teenage troubles -- tContested family practices and moral reasoning: updating concepts for working with family-related social problems -- tWorking with fathers: risk or resource? -- tWhat is at stake in family troubles? Existential issues and value frameworks -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the everyday family lives of children and young people come to be increasingly defined as matters of public policy and concern, it is important to raise the question of how we can understand the contested terrain between “normal” family troubles and troubled and troubling families. In this important, timely and thought-provoking publication, a wide range of contributors explore how “troubles” feature in “normal” families, and how the “normal” features in “troubled” families. Drawing on research on a wide range of substantive topics - including infant care, sibling conflict, divorce, disability, illness, migration and asylum-seeking, substance misuse, violence, kinship care, and forced marriage - the contributors aim to promote dialogue between researchers addressing mainstream family change and diversity in everyday lives, and those specialising in specific problems which prompt professional interventions. In tackling these contentious and difficult issues across a variety of topics, the book addresses a wide audience, including policy makers, service users and practitioners, as well as family studies scholars more generally who are interested in issues of family change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aFamilieszGreat Britain. 0aFamily social workzGreat Britain. 0aParent and childzGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Children's Studies.2bisacsh1 aBoddy, Janet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrady, Geraldine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraun, Dorit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChase, Elaine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChurchill, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClarke, Karen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCooper, Karin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavies, Hayley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuque-Páramo, Maria Claudia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErel, Umut, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/